			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">A common mistake among novice as well as experienced drivers is to underestimate the time or distance it takes for their vehicle to come to a full stop once brakes are applied. Recent research speculates that this phenomenon might be a manifestation of a much more general perceptual illusion called perceptual shifts. Such shifts have been demonstrated when people have to judge the temporal interval between various events.  Results indicate that intervals between causal actions and outcomes (i.e. pressing a key to produce a tone) are systematically underestimated relative to intervals between unrelated events.  One reason for this may be that our mind is predisposed towards contiguous causal relations, meaning that contiguous event pairings are much more likely to be judged as causally related compared to delayed pairings. It is, for instance, trivial to see whether or not a light-switch produces the desired effect; the same is not true, however, for a pedestrian crossing, or a lift, where one does not know when to assume that the light or lift is broken. The same contiguity bias may be at work in the above example, albeit from a reverse direction: Because one is aware of the causal influence one has over the motion of the vehicle, one also assumes that this influence is instantaneous. This argument is a radical extrapolation of the principles of causality, outlined by David Hume more than 250 years ago. If it is correct, it will have wide reaching implications for scientists in the areas of consciousness, perception, and cognition, as well as for designers of user interfaces and Virtual Reality environments, where optimal feedback synchronization is of prime importance.  This project will investigate whether perceptual shifts are indeed grounded on attributed causality in a number of ways. They could be, for instance, a more general byproduct of voluntary actions arising from task demands of action control. If they are truly based on causal relations, these shifts should also occur when observers passively watch causally related event pairs (as opposed to generating them).  Causal relations can be weak or strong: a drug might cause a weak or mild headache, a treatment might work all the time, or only in a few examples.  If perceptual shifts are grounded in causal understanding, then the extent of the shifts should be mediated by the strength of the relation. Furthermore, we know that some causal relations take time to unfold: Aspirin does not cure headaches right away, one needs to wait a while.  Does this mean that when judging the temporal interval between events where delays are expected, one would over-, rather than under-estimate the time?  Finally, in order to identify causal relations, we don't only draw on temporal contiguity, we also use spatial contiguity: the closer two events are in space, the easier it is for us to recognize a causal relation between them because we don't have to look so far.  Does this mean that if we assume that two events are causally related, they automatically appear closer together than they would otherwise?  The work outlined in this proposal attempts to answer these radical questions with a series of very simple experiments.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
